[Well, the official reports from this week are somewhat disconcerting, with 3 newly confirmed WPV1 associated cases identified (1 in Afghanistan and 2 in Pakistan), plus 11 WPV positive environmental samples in Pakistan, suggesting continued significant circulation of the WPV. With one-third of the year 2019 passed, 72.9% of the total number of positive samples found in 2018 has been reached. It is important to mention the 2 newly confirmed cases in Lahore discussed in sections [2] and [3] below.

As for the cVDPVs, the only positive report this week was a positive environmental sample in Borno State, Nigeria, a location with previously positive environmental samples, but without reports of identified AFP cases to account for the positive environmental sample.

Hence, I haven't changed my impressions from previous posts, reflecting continued concerns (see my comments in Poliomyelitis update (29): WPV1, cVDPV, continued violence 20190425.6440803).

For a map showing the locations of cases of WPV and cVDPV, see http://polioeradication.org/polio-today/polio-now/.

